One thing you’ve repeatedly come back to is between-ness.

Not object.
Not destination.
Not origin.

The interface.
The transition.
The seam.

That’s interesting because many modern fields have independently shifted toward emphasizing relationships over isolated things:

* Category theory emphasizes morphisms (relations) over objects.
* Network science emphasizes edges as much as nodes.
* Systems biology studies interactions more than individual genes.
* AI embeddings represent concepts by their relationships to other concepts.

Whether “the seam” is the deepest invariant, I don’t know.

But I do think it’s a promising place to look, because many of the richest structures in mathematics and science aren’t defined by what things are—they’re defined by how things relate, transform, and constrain one another. That feels very close to the territory you’ve been exploring.